In and out of my studio, I experiment with rules. Sometimes I use alter egos‚Äîembodied sets of rules‚Äîto push or disrupt certain predictable outcomes in my work. Each of these personae have a visual language and a mode of operation. This work is four of these studio personae‚ÄîOtto, Santiago, Tammy, and Njezan‚Äîmaking sense of the sound that came through me all those years ago, performing its song in four-part harmony, conducted by me.

So many of us are carrying a lot right now. Personal losses, collective grief, the ache of what is happening in the world, and the grief we feel for our more-than-human kin and planet. We were never meant to carry any of this alone. What does it mean to live and die consciously? This circle is an offering to unburden ourselves in shared community and, in doing so, perhaps find more spaciousness and imaginative possibilities. 

Together we will co-create a sacred space to remember that these tender conversations about death, grief, cycles of change, and all of our connections in this web of existence once lived at the center of our communities. They are an integral part of our collective wellbeing. 

Death Circle is not a therapeutic setting or a grief support group, but an invitation to be present with one another as we explore these topics and reconnect more deeply with ourselves, each other, and the world around us. We welcome your curiosities, stories, questions, as well as your silence. There is no pressure to speak. All of it belongs üñ§

Our hope is that this offering fosters clarity, nurtures care, and deepens our relational intimacy. 

Death Circle will be held on the last Sunday of every month, from 5-7pm. We‚Äôll have coffee and donuts, but feel free to bring your own snacks or any comfort items that support you.

We look forward to seeing you there ‚Äî 
Joshua & Bri

events.description:
We‚Äôre thrilled to spotlight a truly captivating series in our current exhibition, LEAF LITTER‚Äî‚ÄòAbalone Variation 1‚Äì6‚Äô by the talented artist KT Wilson. These original works are a celebration of the subtle, often overlooked wonders of nature, and we invite you to experience them in person at Irving Park Art & Frame.
Each piece in this series features a sustainably sourced abalone shell (pƒÅua) from the pristine waters of New Zealand. Revered for their iridescent beauty and cultural significance, New Zealand abalone shells are harvested under one of the world‚Äôs most robust sustainability systems, ensuring that their natural populations are protected for generations to come. These shells, considered ‚Äòtaonga‚Äô (treasures) in MƒÅori culture, are not only a feast for the eyes but also a testament to the harmony of art and ecological responsibility‚Å†.
KT Wilson‚Äôs approach transforms each shell into a meditative focal point by mounting them in custom shadowbox frames. Rather than traditional fastenings, Wilson uses carefully woven textiles and thread to cradle each shell in place. This technique both secures the shell and highlights its natural form, color, and texture, drawing attention to the unique qualities of each specimen. The interplay between the organic shell and the geometric textile work invites viewers to contemplate the contrast and connection between the natural world and human creativity.
The ‚ÄòAbalone Variation‚Äô series is a perfect fit for LEAF LITTER, our exhibition dedicated to the nuanced, often unnoticed aspects of nature. This show brings together artists whose work delves into the delicate, the intricate, and the ephemeral‚Äîreminding us that beauty is often found in quiet details. KT Wilson‚Äôs pieces exemplify this ethos, offering viewers a chance to slow down and appreciate the subtle complexity of natural materials and thoughtful craft.
.
Visit us at Irving Park Art & Frame to see KT Wilson‚Äôs work and explore the full LEAF LITTER exhibition. Support local art, sustainable materials, and the ongoing conversation between human hands and the natural world.

events.title: ü§ù Native Perennials for Shady Situations - Shannon Currey
events.description:
Hear from two dynamic regional speakers about native plants! Shannon Currey, Education and Outreach for Izel Native Plants, will speak about native perennials for shady situations. Preston Montague, Landscape Architect and Instructor at NC A&T University, will talk about planting native perennials in North Carolina's urban environments. He is an artist working to strengthen relationships between people and the natural world.

üå± Native Perennials for Shady Situations - Shannon Currey, Education and Outreach for Izel Native Plants
Shady spaces in the landscape often get the mulch treatment or are planted with problematic spreaders like liriope or English ivy. Fortunately, there are a variety of native, herbaceous perennials that offer a powerful combination of visual appeal and ecological function. While few plants grow in the dense shade underneath evergreens, shade-tolerant species have developed strategies that allow them to do well in less than full-sun conditions. This session addresses the nature of shade and some of the physiological adaptations that shade-tolerant plants employ. Focusing on regional native species and their cultivars, we‚Äôll take a close look at a selection of perennials, grasses, and sedges to understand why they‚Äôre particularly helpful.

üå± Under the Radar: Planting Perennials in North Carolina's Urban Environments - Preston Montague, Landscape Architect and Instructor at NC A&T University
Join Preston Montague for a conversation about his experience working with herbaceous plantings in his practice, and obstacles and opportunities facing advocates fighting for biodiversity in our cities and developments. Herbaceous plants have tremendous potential to provide for a wide range of ecosystem services, not least of which is boosting biodiversity in our most urban environments, or providing the most basic of shelter for wildlife in new developments in the area. These plants can be orderly, safe, and beautiful year round, even in tough urban environments.

events.title: ü§ù Demonstration Against Injustice
events.description:
Shout out to all the comrades and organizations that have been organizing this demonstration for months, thank you to all the comrades who raised their voices today against injustice and to call for unity in the community, in the class, and to call for solidarity. Today we just wanted to have a demonstration to tell the new administration that here in the Triad we are organized and that there is a resistance that will defend our rights and that if they touch one of us, we will all come out. We invite you, members of the community, whether you are part of an organization or not, who wants to collaborate, who is frustrated with what is happening and doesn‚Äôt know how to help, who want to understand and get more information, we invite you to ORGANIZE yourself by getting in touch with us or any organization that best suits you. We also want to make a call to the organizations that want to do things together to join us, we must open the channels of communication and support each other. We have many different tasks but the adversary is the same and in the end the fight is also for the same thing. So let‚Äôs organize, let‚Äôs fight together!  Please stay tuned for the next events, actions etc.
